04357nam a22007935i 9781400852505DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2014    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008525057 a10.1515/97814008525052doi  a(DE-B1597)454031  a(OCoLC)984627206  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPA3136b.B55 2017 7aLIT0041902bisacsh 7aLIT0200002bisacsh 7aPHI0020002bisacsh 7aPHI0160002bisacsh04a882.01091622231 aBillings, Joshua, eauthor.10aGenealogy of the Tragic :bGreek Tragedy and German Philosophy /cJoshua Billings.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tNote on Translations, Citations, and Abbreviations -- tINTRODUCTION: Tragedy and Philosophy around 1800 -- tTRAGIC MODERNITIES -- tTRAGIC THEMES -- tTRAGIC TEXTS -- tBibliography -- tIndex  aWhy did Greek tragedy and "the tragic" come to be seen as essential to conceptions of modernity? And how has this belief affected modern understandings of Greek drama? In Genealogy of the Tragic, Joshua Billings answers these and related questions by tracing the emergence of the modern theory of the tragic, which was first developed around 1800 by thinkers associated with German Idealism. The book argues that the idea of the tragic arose in response to a new consciousness of history in the late eighteenth century, which spurred theorists to see Greek tragedy as both a unique, historically remote form and a timeless literary genre full of meaning for the present. The book offers a new interpretation of the theories of Schiller, Schelling, Hegel, Hölderlin, and others, as mediations between these historicizing and universalizing impulses, and shows the roots of their approaches in earlier discussions of Greek tragedy in Germany, France, and England. By examining eighteenth-century readings of tragedy and the interactions between idealist thinkers in detail, Genealogy of the Tragic offers the most comprehensive historical account of the tragic to date, as well as the fullest explanation of why and how the idea was used to make sense of modernity. The book argues that idealist theories remain fundamental to contemporary interpretations of Greek tragedy, and calls for a renewed engagement with philosophical questions in criticism of tragedy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aGreek drama (Tragedy)xThemes, motives. 0aTragedyxHistory and criticism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311044418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400852505zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400852505.jpg  a978-3-11-044418-6  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015  a978-3-11-066592-5  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN